.TH NUM 3 "October 1, 1997" "ASIM/LIP6" "MBK UTILITY STRUCTURE DEFINITIONS"
.SH NAME
num \- mbk list of number 
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \fBnum\fP is used to save numbers in a list.
The use of this structure is strongly recommanded, when such a need occurs.
.LP
The declarations needed to work on \fBnum\fP are available in the header file
\fI"/labo/include/mut315.h"\fP, where '\fI315\fP' is the actual mbk version.
.LP
The following C structure describes the list of number :
.RS
.nf
.if n \{\
.ft B \}
.if t \{\
.ft CR \}
.ta 3n 20n 30n
typedef struct num {
	struct num	\(**NEXT;
	long	DATA;
} num_list;
.ft R
.fi
.RE
.TP 20
\fINEXT\fP
Pointer to the next \fBnum\fP of the list.
.TP
\fIDATA\fP
Value of the data.
.TP
Remark :
a specialized memory allocator has been built in order to create and free
\fBnum_list\fPs, so absolutly avoid to create or free them an other way than
through the access functions.
.SH SEE ALSO
